values.QID1_TEXT: I regret listening to my dad who said, "Women can't be lawyers."
Being more willing to risk failure in both my career and my relationships as growth requires risk and sometimes failure.
I regret not going to Air Force Officer Candidate School.

I regret trying to fit into a mold that I thought I was supposed to fit into - rather than doing what I wanted to do.  And, I don't mean - becoming a dentist when I wanted to be an artist.  I mean - more like following the social norms of the corporate world because laughing in meetings was unacceptable - even though having fun is fun.  Come to find out IDEO encourages people to laugh and have fun and look how creative their people are?  No Hard Feelings has taught me that there is a time and place for your emotions, sure - and laughing at inappropriate moments - not ok...  - but, there are so many times when I stifled the real me.  And, for what?
That I didn't  became entrepreneur earlier in nu career
Taking better care of my health.
abortions
not being courageous enough to be a better parent

I had a really wonderful, beautiful, fun girlfriend who became long-distance, and we weren't able to keep it going. She'll always be the one that got away. I'm happily married with three kids now, but I'll always wonder "what if?"

Not developing better basic habits when I was younger: flossing my teeth regularly; eating more vegetables regularly; getting 8 hours of sleep regularly; being on time regularly; going to church regularly; exercising regularly. I've made a lot of mistakes and had a lot of success. I've taken some risks that paid off and others that resulted in a crash-and-burn.  But I regret not developing better regular habits that would probably would have made failures less severe and made successes longer lived.
Not pursuing fields or activities I enjoyed/ was interested in/ had an aptitude for out of fear and anxiety.

To your point, I regret not making more out of my college experience in two ways. I was too focused on getting good grades (I graduated with a 3.95 GPA Summa Cum Laude) and on fitting in (I joined a sorority, which was totally not a fit for me). In hindsight, I wish I'd taken classes that would've broadened my horizons more, even if they were challenging and meant I might not have gotten that near-perfect GPA. And I wish I'd explored other ways of meeting people that are more aligned with my interests and values today--school newspaper, community service, endurance sports. I probably also went to the wrong school for me--UCLA. It was the safe choice, while the school I almost went to--Northwestern--would have been more of a risk for this California girl but probably a better place for me to learn and grow. Still, I'm happy with my life today, so can I really say I regret anything about what got me here?
I wasn’t kinder to myself in my younger days.
Not recognizing earlier and leaving toxic / negative relationships sooner.
I did not get out doing more outdoor activities.

I spent too much time on looking after my two kids, and my career suffered. My kids who are now in their late teens, show few results of all that time (it may be that late teens, when their goal seems to be about asserting individuality is a poor time to judge parenting results) but I sure regret all those extra curricular classes and play dates and activities etc. (Learning to do chores would have been more productive and useful to them). I wasted the bloom of my brain and health on trivial parenting duties, and they would have been just fine with half the attention.
Not working/studying harder in college

Not exploring and taking part in a more diverse set of activities when I was younger (in High School and College in particular). I realize now that I focused too much on academics and activities that just dropped in my lap rather than searching for things that I might truly love. 

For example, I'm sure there were many classes and clubs for people interested in creative writing in college. But I never pursued any of them. But after I graduated I became very interested in creative writing and joined writing groups. I wonder if there are other interests I'd love now if I had tried them back then.
Not sticking with my gut to teach right out of college. I listened to others' opinions rather than my own.
That I masked/covered my anxiety and depression rather than listening to and facing it for most of my life.
Not taking the first offer for my house. I lost a lot of money because of that.
Focusing on myself, my thoughts, fears , opinions, how I was perceived instead of being totally present and listening
Not being more forward thinking.
Worrying about money too much.  Not spending = missing out on experiences.
Not having a proper affair, relationship.

That I spent a lot more time working than playing. I worked a lot of weekends (not for extra money) just to excel at my work, or to rehab our home and property. I never really just kicked back and played much.

Standing by and letting people get bullied.  Didn't do too much bullying myself, though did on occasion, but did not step forward when it occurred and while maybe not able to stop it, at least go on record.  I undoubted would have suffered the consequence (pain) of going against the grain "back then" (mostly high school)  in exchange for peace of mind today that I had taken a positive step.
I regret staying in a bad marriage for 30 years.  Should have gotten divorced long ago, & now realize it will just keep getting harder & harder to leave as I get older.
Not going to Williams College
That I didn’t really listen to my Dad and ask him more questions before he died. We were very close but I still feel I missed an opportunity.
Wish I’d Learned more of the Classics. I could have taken more literature and language classes in college but kept within my major, bypassing the great smorgasbord of learning opportunities offered.
Being afraid to try something new.
That I was not able to make sure a dear friend knew how much I loved and admired her before she passed away.
I didn't take more risks throughout life.
Not taking the time to visit, hike, and enjoy our National Parks. Five years ago I had bone cancer & now can't walk.

Ignoring the "red flags" when choosing a marriage partner.  If you have concerns about your partner's personality, behaviors, or suitability for you before marriage (for example if they are dishonest, unkind, unloving, etc.) - when you are both likely displaying your best behavior - those issues will still be there after marriage, and will likely get worse with the stresses and strains of married life (finances, children, health issues, family dynamics, etc.)  It all "worked out" in that we divorced  after 14 years and I was able to create a good and healthy life for myself and my children.  But if I knew then, what I know now, I would not have married him in the first place.   What I have NO regrets about:  the two wonderful children that resulted from our union and who are beautiful, loving, kind, honest, and responsible humans.
I regret spending time worrying about getting hurt and less time living and doing.

That I didn't believe I could have children. My husband convinced me it was possible and I just needed to BELIEVE and have FAITH! Thanks to reproductive technology and experts I have a son! I wish I believed earlier and I may have had more children. :)
Not making better choices--scholastic, personal, social--during my time in college.
Not getting a specialized or specific college degree. I have a general 4-year degree.

When I was seven my father died. Within the year I had an accident where I lost the vision in my right eye. I regret being bitter and not better. Too many family and friends had to endure the bitter years. By the way, for the last 30-35 years, I have been better not bitter and I would say that everyday  I still think of that regret and that drives behaviour to this day.
I was a More conscientious learner
Making the easy, comfortable choices instead of risking and holding out for the right thing (person, job,etc)

Letting someone talk me into starting my own business, even though it turns out I am not cut out for the downsides: Financial stress; having to hawk myself 24/7; always having to be "on;" missing the structure and the social element of working as a real employed person on a team. Seventeen years in, I have run through all of my savings, and now appear to be unemployable, so I may be stuck with my circumstances.
Not being more outgoing social positive bold and taking risks in my 20s.
I regret that my husband and I bought a single home as newlyweds, rather than renting an apartment or townhouse first.
Not saving enough for retirement
Not speaking up when someone disrespected another person or group because we were in an environment where we should be “civil” ( e.g., work).  I regret not upholding my own values.
Quitting my yoga routine after college

I worried too much about what other people thought of me (or what I thought they thought of me) and allowed that to hold me back.  I wish I had allowed myself to dream bigger and set outrageous goals....and tried to reach them.  I regret leaving so much of my life to chance and to be so influenced by what I thought other people did or would think about me and my choices.
The relationship damage I caused due to my clumsy coping with PTSD.
Staying at a company too long...longevity/loyalty is not as important as I was told/taught 20 years ago.
An automobile accident which left my younger daughter with a scar on her forehead.  She was only 2, and hasn't seemed bothered by it since, but I still regret it.
Not moving to the East Coast when the opportunity was ripe.
It taking a new career opportunity
Not choosing to major in psychology

I regret not staying on my educational path, right out of high school. I wanted to attend college out of state and become a professional student. I just finished my bachelor's degree two years ago and no longer have a desire to work on my masters.

I regret my choice of colleges and career.  This started the dominoes falling which led to more regrets and bad decisions.  It really comes down to - listen to your parents:  they are not that dumb and might even know a thing or 2 that are very helpful.
Focusing too much on succeeding at projects/tasks and not enough on building enduring relationships with people who help me stretch, grow and be better.
I wish I'd picked college based on academics rather than athletics.
I regret how much sun exposure i got without wearing sunscreen. i regret not double majoring in a science.
Not getting my PhD

At age 24 I was living in NYC hoping to become a famous painter.  After much ado I was able to show my portfolio to the Holly Solomon Gallery, the hottest gallery of that time.  I was doing works on paper about 18"x24", When I showed my portfolio they said they loved my work but needed artists who could do 10'x10' painting that sold for thousands of dollars and works on paper that could sell for a few hundred.  They said they could not break even having a show of only works on paper.  Instead of heeding their wise advice and going home and knocking some large works, I turned up my "artiste" nose and thought "I have nothing to say in a large format, too bad for them"  If I could go back in time I would slap the s**t out of  that snotty, little "artiste"!!
Needlessly unkind things said.

When my maternal grandfather passed away, it was “go time” for the funeral, and we were staying with family (had to travel to a different state). My mom asked, “Do you want to attend the service?” I said, “No” because I was freaked out. Regretted it as soon as the car left the driveway without me. I know it’s nonsense to think “I didn’t say goodbye”, but I still regret that.
Not calling the people I love enough
I regret not having more leadership work related opportunities
I regret not saying ‘yes’ more iften

I should have joined the military when I was 19 and wanted to. I’ve been in the Reserves for three years now and love it! but I’m really conscious that my life path would have been so different if I’d joined when I was younger (friendships, social groups, experiences, ...) Still, I find it more helpful to look forward and see what I can still achieve, rather than backwards to what could have been.

Beeing more relaxed and not having as many ”musts’” when my children where infants and up to 5 years old. I thougt that by having clean home and dinner ready st 17.30 would make me a perfect mom and wife. I wish I hadn’t stressen about it the way I did.
Wasting too much time worrying about boys liking me, which lead to some poor decisions that could have had disastrous consequences.
Being too generalized and not deep diving enough into the harder, more focused areas that would provide more leverage later in life.
Looking for a different job when I already had a good one...fortunately I didn’t change jobs but I wasted too much time in interviews etc.

I wish I had learned emotional control at a much, much younger age. I made it a point to instill good habits of emotional control in my kids as they were growing and I see how they do not struggle in some ways I still do.
That I started writing earlier in life so that I was already an established writer.
Marrying so young.
I regret not being more helpful to my parents.
That I didn’t get an Ivy League education.
I wish that the technology tools we have today would have been available when I was in my teens and 20s.
I did not complete my degree
I regret not deeply pursuing non-academic hobbies while I had time between graduating from university and entering the work-force.

I wish I had purchased a church with grounds that was in my neighborhood while I was in my 20s.  It was available and within my grasp (barely) and I wanted to turn it into a music venue and guitar school.  I chickened out at the last minute as I was single and not sure of how I would get it all done.  Now, I know I could have.

Looking back on 43 years of marriage, I married the wrong person even though I knew we would not, perhaps could not, be happy together.  As his recent widow, I still don't fully know why I made this terrible decision.
Not taking a chance and going for a more creative career.
holding grudges/being bitter.  It steals my joy, reduces my hope, and saps my energy as it isolates me from my community.

I stopped investing in myself after I finished my college degree.   Instead of spending my discretionary income on books, healthy living (diet & exercise), and personal growth, I used the discretionary income to pay down debt and buy stuff that I don't need or use regularly (electronics, for example).  In short, I wish I had used more of my money in my late 20s and early 30s to continue to learn and less of my money on toys.
getting married the first time
I didn't pay enough attention when my children were young. I was there, but I didn't stop and think about what a great joy I was experiencing.
I regret that I allowed myself to be complacent in work and not be driven more fully.

Not getting a good mentor or coach to help me with career and money decisions.
While I have done well enough, I feel that I have left a lot on the table.  Regrets, maybe.  But it is really having missed not only business\career opportunities, but time with family, travel, community time.  I dare not say a wasted life, but one that could have been much richer.  I work much harder on that now, the richness, living more in the moment than the future and trying not to have past regrets.
Not travelling before I had kids.

Not having the insight earlier in my life to find someone who would challenge me to be the REAL me. I've spent too many years trying to be what other people think is a happy or successful person. I'm just now learning how to be honest about what I want--and get it.
Some decisions about my studies

I have more than one but like you, I wish I'd spent my college years more boldly and profitably.  I smoked too much pot and played too much backgammon.  I got all A's but I could have done a lot more outside of my classwork than I did.

I was not able to attend the large co-ed university that was my dream school because my mother wanted me to go to a smaller all women's college. I had attended a large high school and was one of the top students in my class. The smaller college was very strong academically so I still received an excellent education.  I was able to transfer to the university as a junior, but the experience was not the same as going as a freshman.

None. 
Every decision I have made in my life has brought me to this moment. If I change one thing, no matter how small, who knows what the ripple effect would bring, or take away. So I regret nothing. And if I am unhappy with this moment in time, my energy is better spent in working to change my present, a true possibility, whereas all efforts to change the past are futile. [Unless Doctor Who comes along, then all bets are off :)]
My divorce.
I wish I wouldn't have dated in High School.
I regret working overtime when my daughter was young.
Never took a semester abroad in college.

Not taking the time to enjoy the moment. I wish I had worried less and not let anxiety and stress control the moment. Just with I had taken the time and enjoyed some of the experiences and big moments in my life more.
Not being more gentle with my son as he was growing up.

If I can only have one: --ask for help more

If I can have another: --ask more questions
Trying to fit in with the wrong group by making the wrong impressions.
Not standing up for myself and allowing my parents to push me into studying at university a subject that I wasn’t interested in.
bullying kids in my high school

I regret not doing something about my mental health problems (ie medication) when I was 20 instead of 35. I wasted 15 years of my life being unwell, not fulfilling my potential and suffering. Now at 42 I am still catching up and carrying the scars in my brain that make it hard for me to excel.

I also know that I didn't know what was happening to me and no-one helped me, so I guess I can only try to help others realise life can be better, with the rest of mine.
Not trusting my gut and pulling out of a bad business-client relationship sooner.
I wish I had saved more money so I am not catching up now.
That I did not go into the entertainment industry.
Getting divorced from my children's father after 25 years together
Not speaking at my grandmother's memorial service.
That I didn't have the courage to let go of what everyone else thought and find a way to study more overseas.
I wish I'd realized how possible and how varied my choices were within life - to study abroad, to branch into many different studies, to succeed on my own.
Not traveling more
I wish I wasn't so hard on my parents as a teenager
passing by some opportunities that presented themselves, but I didn't think I was ready for them. Bad idea. I should have jumped at the chance.

Being judgmental of people when I was in middle school and then later at my first job after university. In both instances, I lost friends over being self-righteous. I definitely regret my behaviour as it felt like I was upholding some sort of standard but really it was just destructive.
Following a strong scholarly interest rather than something that would make a good career choice...
Not traveling more - within the US and abroad
not getting proper marriage counseling prior to getting married
Sinking in debt
Not valuing my contributions enough early on
Too much focus on work and achievement, which was and still is important, but not enough focus on play - just as important.
I should have had more sex when I was younger...not that I wasn't trying
Not studying/living abroad in my 20's

Military service.
We live in a GREAT Country; we should serve it!

I wish I had taken more risks in jobs and in life - been braver in speaking up for myself and others - been less lazy and instead set and acted on goals for myself - despite having done alright for myself, I feel I have underachieved on my potential and made my life less than it could have been.
Marrying the person I married. I made the decision for the wrong reason.
Not realising, prior to getting married, that the man I married and had children with would become an alcoholic.
Not getting my four year degree.

I regret not knowing what I wanted to "be" in my life; not taking the time (in my 20s) to find out what would make me happiest as my life work and to pursue that.

Bonus regret: not travelling the world while I was young and had no responsibilities.

I regret not pursuing a medical degree instead of education. I felt pressured by my parents to focus on education because it's what they wanted for me, and what they said they would pay for, instead of me pursuing medicine.
Not going into broadcasting
not getting proper marriage counseling prior to getting married
not being closer to family and friends
Not going in for the kiss with the cute girl I had been hanging out with for a few weeks in college.  Ended up in the friend zone.

I wish I had committed myself to being more authentically me much earlier in my career.  Finding your passion and talents to enable you to say no to those activities that don't edify you can be powerful in helping you sidestep positions that don't lift you up, but drag you down.
Saved mored, I´m about to be a father, and I wish I expensed more wisely.

While I have been successful in my career and reached heights I never thought I would achieve, I wish I had taken a more ambitious path. I easily cleared the high jump bar at 6’. I wish I had set it much higher. I love my father and appreciate all he did for me, however, he taught me to take the sure road - risk is bad. I raised both of my boys to aim high and stretch themselves. Calculated risk isn’t bad. Failure is not the end, but part of the journey. The learnings from failures can propel you to greatness. Both of my boys are doing very well in medical school! One wants to be a surgeon and the other an ophthalmologist. They will both do great things!

I wish I had a wider world view on the plethora of roles and directions I could have taken. As the first in my family to attend university, I settled for teaching as my boyfriends sister was a teacher. I have had a wonderful career so far, spanning 3 industries and 3 countries, all of my roles have been education focussed so my teaching degree was a good stepping stone but I wish I had been exposed to more careers before I made those choices. I also wish I had saved / invested the big bucks I earned whilst working in IT. Mind you, those 6 years were full of amazing travel experiences and I was also able to help our family members who were struggling.
I wish that I had applied for a federal clerkship for after law school. I feel like I missed out by going straight to a law firm instead of even trying to clerk for a judge.
I regret never having children with my second wife.  I had one child with my first wife and I helped raise my 2 step children with my second wife, but we did not have any children together.
That i didn't get into adventure motorcycle riding sooner. And adventuring in a grander way.

I regret that my fiancé and I did not discuss significant issues before we married. If we had, we might have learned to communicate better with each other, and/or we might have decided not to get married after all.  Either way, we might have spared ourselves years of unhappiness and the stress of divorce.

I regret not studying abroad during college. I missed the opportunity of a lifetime to travel with a wonderful professor, who knew Italy like the back of his hand. I was too stubborn to ask my parents for the money.
Staying in a dead end marriage
I  have put much efforts to make a good family and payed less attention to my career . I should have concentrated on it earlier.
Trying too hard to work within the system
I wish that I had paid more attention to, and put more value on, my inner/innate wisdom.  I wish that the adults in my life had valued my inner wisdom.

I most sincerely regret the fact that I was not honest with myself or my ex-partner about the state of our relationship and waited until I was already in another relationship to end a partnership of over a decade.  
I have absolutely no excuse for what I see as profoundly cowardly and unprincipled behaviour and I am disappointed and saddened by this episode in my life even though it happened over 20 years ago.  
My regret can be categorised in several ways:  (a) I regret that I did not really know myself, I did not know what I wanted and I did not take the time to work that through with the help of others; (b) I regret that I went for what looked like an easy option and certainly I regret going for something that flattered my already inflated ego; (c) I regret that I did not try to work at and remedy something that was good, that had real honesty and potential; (d) I regret treating someone I loved and still deeply love so badly - with hurting them so profoundly - and with damaging so many other relationships around us both in the process.   

(By the way I LOVE what you do - so thank you!  I have read all your books and came to listen to you at the RSA in London.)
not learning to appreciate money and understanding the time value of money earlier in life (so I'm teaching it to my kids!)

One significant regret that I have is not pursuing my dream of becoming a musician to the fullest extent just because I thought that I did not have "what it took." I am blessed with an amazing family and a very fulfilling career, but I do catch myself sometimes wondering, "What if....?"
That I didn't take time to get to know myself vs my parents' desires for me before college and wound up in the wrong major.
Having networked more with people. Today I have huge network with c-levels and executives. Wish I had started sooner

Placing too much importance on MY expectations on my kids and not appreciating their amazing, unique qualities. I could have been kinder and given them space to flourish where I now see their self doubt has taken root. I don’t know if I can forgive myself but after recognizing my faults I work to do better every day with them.
Not using enough advisors on significant career changes.
I wish i was more open and vocal about how i feel

I had a job offer at Proctor & Gamble as a manufacturing line manager out of college.  I instead chose to go to graduate school.  Had I gone to P&G, I likely would have had a career moving into their Marketing and becoming a consumer products expert.

But I don't have too many regrets.  By choosing to go to graduate school, I met my wife.  Having been married for 23 years, I made the right personal decision.
I didn't take enough risk.
My choice of Masters degree program. It was a great experience, but not very practical or applicable to my 'current' life.

I was a stay at home Mom and devoted lots of time to my kids but I regret not getting them more involved with social concerns..helping the poor, environmental issues.  To be more concerned for the less fortunate.
I wish I had studied music
I regret working too much when my children were young.
That I didn't maximize my course selections while in university.
Choosing things that I knew I could succeed at as opposed to pushing into an area where failure, or being less successful could be the outcome.
That I never learned how to feel safe in water - like learning how to swim.
My significant regret is not choosing a career path earlier.  I drifted for ten years before remotely settling into a field.  I am always the oldest in my profession.
I should have been more of a risk taker in my business career. Take more risks in job assignment and in exploring work with another company.

While I have made what some might characterize as worthy achievements, my significant regret is that I did not fully honor the promise of my potential and in many cases self-doubt reinforced by "old tapes" suggested I would mess up and thus I would incur self-fulfilling prophecies.
I regret not having/adopting children.
Holding my young stepdaughters at a distance because they had a mom (who I despised- another regret) not acknowledging that they had room in their lives (and hearts) for 2 moms.
I wished I was more of a stand up person, not afraid to speak up or stand out for the greater good and for my own personal life.
Not telling my parents that I wanted to play sports
That I was not bolder (I am a woman in a male dominated industry) in my youth.
Spending thousands of dollars on training for Stock Options trading.
I stayed too long (17+ yrs) in an unhealthy relationship
That I didn't help my sons forge a stronger bond between them
Not doing a personal development course 20 years earlier (like The Landmark Forum which I did at 44) to distinguish self created and self limiting beliefs.
not having the courage to finish university, get formal qualifications for my field and go after my career dreams..played small and safe and always did what was right for the family first
Not finishing my Boy Scout Eagle Scout requirements
I dont do regrets, too much wasted energy. I make the best decision at the time and dont look back!
Deciding to have a baby so young
More actively pursuing sports
No regrets. Every single decision I’ve ever made is a part of my story and who I am today. I accept who I am today and where I am. Everything happens for a reason.
that I did not marry or have a significant other in my life
Getting married the first time when I didn't understand what it meant and wasn't committed for life.
Not pausing and embracing the current 'season of life'. Too much looking forward.

I wish I had studied abroad for a year in college, rather than stay because I was worried about "leaving my boyfriend". I look back at that moment and cringe - and wish I could go back to my 19 year old self and force her on the plane - because the relationship ultimately ended... and I missed out on living and learning in France for a year.
That I did not get my HR Certificate when I was in my 30's - I ended up getting it at 52.
I wish I would have been more focused in high school and went to college or university right after HS. Not wait till later in life.
Going to prison
I partied too much and did not notice what was happening around me.
Getting married too young.
Not taking the opportunity to serve my country.

Allowing a bully boss to make me sick.  I wish I had been proactive in the situation rather than letting the bullying impact on my health.  

While I was on sick leave I learned a lot through reading books (The No Asshold Rule was essential reading), reaching out to the Employee Assistance Plan and getting some counseling (communication patterns - adult-child, adult-adult...), and time to reflect and plan a way forward.  I just wish I hadn't allowed it to so far.  My health is much more important than any job.

To have been bolder at a younger age. Not stupid, not crazy, no drugs or alcohol. But things like skydiving, race car driving, volunteering for more dangerous duty while I was in the Navy. That way I’d have more cool things to tell my grandkids about, instead of stories of other people I knew! Ha. Was always kind to people, so no regrets there.
I didn't learn from my mistakes.  Finally, at 68, I'm reflecting on what I learned from a decision that led to either a good or bad outcome and how I can improve my results in the future.
Not taking the time to fully investigate my interests, talents, and career options before entering college and the workforce.
Having sex for the first time with the wrong person.
I regret not visiting my uncle more often.

I have done a lot of things; travel, education, and career have all been positive experiences and I found myself thinking about many things that I haven't regretted (using money to travel rather than buy that dream car, student loan to get a teaching degree, having children young, career choice) so this exercise was actually a positive experience as I couldn't ignore the 'non example' of regrets and that felt good to do so. The one regret was not an event or moment but more of a state of mind in that I wish I was more self confident with position in life and choices I made. I feel I spent too many years doubting if I was 'good enough' and therefore maybe spent more time with work duties compared to family and spouse duties. I see 'myself' in young ambitious colleagues and wish I could impart to them what I know now about what is really important...and that is the strength of the relationships to the people close to you. Equally important is the comfort and confidence within you to know that you don't have to long for 'more' and to take the time to enjoy what you do have and not burn up time thinking or longing for what you don't have. I regret not knowing that earlier in life.
That I did not go to university
I regret not practicing the guitar harder, not pushing more to play in a band.
Money planning.  If you start young and continue, you can really have a nice chunk of change set aside.  Managing debt also makes a big difference.
I regret not taking more care of my body from a younger age - I ran lots and got injured lots. I now have a more balanced approach and do strength training and yoga.
I regret that I did not go to college. I was too scared.
Leaving the Army after 8 years instead of staying at least 20 years and securing the retirement benefits

Not moving to join my sister in South Carolina out of state right after I graduated from college. It was a great opportunity, but I was too connected to my then boyfriend.  (One good thing was that I had the sense not to marry him at least!)  :)
Not having talked more frankly and openly with the love of my life. I let him go on a stupid misunderstanding and regretted it ever since. (I was about 33 years old at the time)

Not taking art classes at school, instead I took Latin and Greek at the insistence of my parents. It is only recently (within the past 5 years) that I have discovered the joy of creating art for myself and I regret all of the missed years.
Asking my wife to marry me and not divorcing when I should have.

When I was young I was told what I should and shouldn’t study, could and couldn’t do or be, or was told nothing at all, by my parents, about what was possible. I believed it. 
Took me thirty years to wake up. Wrote my first best selling book at 51.
That I didn't learn to be more empathetic until I had about 5 years of experience as a leader of others.
Not pursuing my dreams of entering the world of showbiz (as an actor or director) for fear of rejection and failure.

Only 3-4 students were chosen to represent the hundreds on the school roll. I should have been thrilled when my name was announced, but my friend missed out, and, such was her influence and control, I felt compelled to decline. The music teacher contacted my parents and all three spent days imploring me to reconsider. I stubbornly refused. On the night of the performance, I regretted not being up on stage - the group appeared to be having so much fun. But the greater regret, the part that has stayed with me all my life, has been knowing that I didn’t take the chance that came my way because I succumbed to pressure from a person who felt no joy over my achievement; only bitterness as a result of her own disappointment. I’ve always been grateful for the lesson, but the choice I made remains a deep regret.
